docs.snippet: Inspired by the success of Pokemon Go, a Belgian primary school headmaster has developed an online game for people to search for books instead of cartoon monsters, attracting tens of thousands of players in weeks.

headline.print_headline: Belgians Are Hunting Books, Instead of Pokemon
headline.main: Belgians Are Hunting Books, Instead of Pokemon

docs.snippet: A gunman shot one person dead and injured two more at a senior living center in Wyoming before killing himself on Wednesday, police said.

headline.print_headline: Gunman Kills One, Self at Wyoming Senior Facility
headline.main: Gunman Kills One, Self at Wyoming Senior Facility

docs.snippet: Russian Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev said on Tuesday a decision by the Court of Arbitration for Sport (CAS) to uphold a ban on Russia's participation in next month's Rio Paralympics was "cynical" and a blow to all disabled people.

headline.print_headline: Russian PM Medvedev: CAS Decision on Paralympics a Blow to All Disabled People
headline.main: Russian PM Medvedev: CAS Decision on Paralympics a Blow to All Disabled People

docs.snippet: A video of an enraged tuk-tuk driver unloading on the state of Egypt's flagging economy went viral on Thursday, underlining growing popular discontent in the country over shortages of food staples and broader business malaise.

headline.print_headline: Raging Tuk-Tuk Driver Bashes Egypt Economy, Video Goes Viral
headline.main: Raging Tuk-Tuk Driver Bashes Egypt Economy, Video Goes Viral

docs.snippet: The International Olympics Committee is confident China will guarantee uncensored internet when it hosts the 2022 Winter Games, a senior IOC official said on Wednesday, though China has given no details about how its pledge will work.

headline.main: IOC Says Confident on Free Internet for Beijing 2022 Olympics
